# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: obd-ii
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Electronic systems have become an increasingly large component of the cost of an automobile, from only around 1% of its value in 1950 to around 30% in 2010.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Modern electric cars rely on power electronics for the main propulsion motor control, as well as managing the battery system.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Future autonomous cars will rely on powerful computer systems, an array of sensors, networking, and satellite navigation, all of which will require electronics.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The earliest electronic systems available as factory installations were vacuum tube car radios, starting in the early 1930s.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The development of semiconductors after World War II greatly expanded the use of electronics in automobiles, with solid-state diodes making the automotive alternator the standard after about 1960, and the first transistorized ignition systems appearing in 1963.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The emergence of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology led to the development of modern automotive electronics.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Dawon Kahng summarized in a Bell Labs memo the achievement: E.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] This led to the development of the power MOSFET by Hitachi in 1969, and the single-chip microprocessor by Federico Faggin, Marcian Hoff, Masatoshi Shima and Stanley Mazor at Intel in 1971.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The development of MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) chips and microprocessors made a range of automotive applications economically feasible in the 1970s.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for the Japanese automobile industry, used for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, dashboard, and engine control.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which utilized the Toshiba TLCS-12 PMOS microprocessor, went into mass production in 1975.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] In 1978, the Cadillac Seville featured a "trip computer" based on a 6802 microprocessor.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Electronically-controlled ignition and fuel injection systems allowed automotive designers to achieve vehicles meeting requirements for fuel economy and lower emissions, while still maintaining high levels of performance and convenience for drivers.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Today's automobiles contain a dozen or more processors, in functions such as engine management, transmission control, climate control, antilock braking, passive safety systems, navigation, and other functions.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The power MOSFET and the microcontroller, a type of single-chip microcomputer, led to significant advances in electric vehicle technology.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] MOSFET power converters allowed operation at much higher switching frequencies, made it easier to drive, reduced power losses, and significantly reduced prices, while single-chip microcontrollers could manage all aspects of the drive control and had the capacity for battery management.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used in vehicles such as automobiles, cars, trucks, electric vehicles, and smart cars.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used for the electronic control unit (ECU), while the power MOSFET and IGBT are used as the load drivers for automotive loads such as motors, solenoids, ignition coils, relays, heaters and lamps.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] In 2000, the average mid-range passenger vehicle had an estimated $100–200 of power semiconductor content, increasing by a potential 3–5 times for electric and hybrid vehicles.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] As of 2017, the average vehicle has over 50 actuators, typically controlled by power MOSFETs or other power semiconductor devices.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Another important technology that enabled modern highway-capable electric cars is the lithium-ion battery.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] It was invented by John Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino in the 1980s, and commercialized by Sony and Asahi Kasei in 1991.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The lithium-ion battery was responsible for the development of electric vehicles capable of long-distance travel, by the 2000s.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] On average, a 2020s car has 50–150 chips, according to Chris Isidore of CNN Business.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] One of the most demanding electronic parts of an automobile is the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Engine controls demand one of the highest real-time deadlines, as the engine itself is a very fast and complex part of the automobile.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Of all the electronics in any car, the computing power of the engine control unit is the highest, typically a 32-bit processor.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] A modern car may have up to 100 ECU's and a commercial vehicle up to 40.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Many more engine parameters are actively monitored and controlled in real-time.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 50 that measure pressure, temperature, flow, engine speed, oxygen level and NOx level plus other parameters at different points within the engine.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] All these sensor signals are sent to the ECU, which has the logic circuits to do the actual controlling.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The ECU output is connected to different actuators for the throttle valve, EGR valve, rack (in VGTs), fuel injector (using a pulse-width modulated signal), dosing injector and more.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 30 actuators in all.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] These control the transmission system, mainly the shifting of the gears for better shift comfort and to lower torque interrupt while shifting.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Automatic transmissions use controls for their operation, and also many semi-automatic transmissions having a fully automatic clutch or a semi-auto clutch (declutching only).
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The engine control unit and the transmission control exchange messages, sensor signals and control signals for their operation.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] All of the above systems form an infotainment system.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Developmental methods for these systems vary according to each manufacturer.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Different tools are used for both hardware and software development.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] These are new generation hybrid ECUs that combine the functionalities of multiple ECUs of Infotainment Head Unit, Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS), Instrument Cluster, Rear Camera/Parking Assist, Surround View Systems etc.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] This saves on the cost of electronics as well as mechanical/physical parts like interconnects across ECUs etc.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] There is also a more centralized control so data can be seamlessly exchanged between the systems.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Given the complexity of this hybrid system, a lot more rigor is needed to validate the system for robustness, safety and security.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] For example, if the infotainment system's application which could be running an open-source Android OS is breached, there could be possibility of hackers to take control of the car remotely and potentially misuse it for anti-social activities.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Typically so, usage of a hardware+software enabled hypervisors are used to virtualize and create separate trust and safety zones that are immune to each other's failures or breaches.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Lot of work is happening in this area and potentially will have such systems soon if not already.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] In order to minimize the risk of dangerous failures, safety-related electronic systems have to be developed following the applicable product liability requirements.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Disregard for, or inadequate application of these standards can lead to not only personal injuries, but also severe legal and economic consequences such as product cancellations or recalls.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The IEC 61508 standard, generally applicable to electrical/electronic/programmable safety-related products, is only partially adequate for automotive-development requirements.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Consequently, for the automotive industry, this standard is replaced by the existing ISO 26262, currently released as a Final Draft International Standard (FDIS).
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] ISO/DIS 26262 describes the entire product life-cycle of safety-related electrical/electronic systems for road vehicles.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] It has been published as an international standard in its final version in November 2011.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The implementation of this new standard will result in modifications and various innovations in the automobile electronics development process, as it covers the complete product life-cycle from the concept phase until its decommissioning.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] As more functions of the automobile are connected to short- or long-range networks, cybersecurity of systems against unauthorized modification is required.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] With critical systems such as engine controls, transmission, airbags, and braking connected to internal diagnostic networks, remote access could result in a malicious intruder altering the function of systems or disabling them, possibly causing injuries or fatalities.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Every new interface presents a new "attack surface".
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] The same facility that allows the owner to unlock and start a car from a smartphone app also presents risks due to remote access.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Auto manufacturers may protect the memory of various control microprocessors both to secure them from unauthorized changes and also to ensure only manufacturer-authorized facilities can diagnose or repair the vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] Systems such as keyless entry rely on cryptographic techniques to ensure "replay" or "man-in-the-middle attacks" attacks cannot record sequences to allow later break-in to the automobile.
[src:obd-ii/automotive-electronics] In 2015 the German general automobile club commissioned an investigation of the vulnerabilities of one manufacturer's electronics system, which could have led to such exploits as unauthorized remote unlocking of the vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:obd-ii/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:obd-ii/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] SAE standard J1979 defines many OBD-II PIDs.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] All on-road vehicles and trucks sold in North America are required to support a subset of these codes, primarily for state mandated emissions inspections.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Manufacturers also define additional PIDs specific to their vehicles.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Though not mandated, many motorcycles also support OBD-II PIDs.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] In 1996, light duty vehicles (less than 8,500 lb or 3,900 kg) were the first to be mandated followed by medium duty vehicles (8,500–14,000 lb or 3,900–6,400 kg) in 2005.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] They are both required to be accessed through a standardized data link connector defined by SAE J1962.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Heavy duty vehicles (greater than 14,000 lb or 6,400 kg) made after 2010, for sale in the US are allowed to support OBD-II diagnostics through SAE standard J1939-13 (a round diagnostic connector) according to CARB in title 13 CCR 1971.1.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Some heavy duty trucks in North America use the SAE J1962 OBD-II diagnostic connector that is common with passenger cars, notably Mack and Volvo Trucks, however they use 29 bit CAN identifiers (unlike 11 bit headers used by passenger cars).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] There are 10 diagnostic services described in the latest OBD-II standard SAE J1979.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Before 2002, J1979 referred to these services as "modes".
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Vehicle manufacturers are not required to support all services.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each manufacturer may define additional services above #9 (e.g.: service 22 as defined by SAE J2190 for Ford/GM, service 21 for Toyota) for other information e.g. the voltage of the traction battery in a hybrid electric vehicle (HEV).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The nonOBD UDS services start at 0x10 to avoid overlap of ID-range.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The table below shows the standard OBD-II PIDs as defined by SAE J1979.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The expected response for each PID is given, along with information on how to translate the response into meaningful data.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Again, not all vehicles will support all PIDs and there can be manufacturer-defined custom PIDs that are not defined in the OBD-II standard.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Note that services 01 and 02 are basically identical, except that service 01 provides current information, whereas service 02 provides a snapshot of the same data taken at the point when the last diagnostic trouble code was set.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The exceptions are PID 01, which is only available in service 01, and PID 02, which is only available in service 02.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] If service 02 PID 02 returns zero, then there is no snapshot and all other service 02 data is meaningless.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] When using Bit-Encoded-Notation, quantities like C4 means bit 4 from data byte C.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each bit is numbered from 0 to 7, so 7 is the most significant bit and 0 is the least significant bit (See below).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Service 02 accepts the same PIDs as service 01, with the same meaning, but information given is from when the freeze frame was created.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Note that PID $02 is used to obtain the DTC that triggered the freeze frame.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A person has to send the frame number in the data section of the message.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Some of the PIDs in the above table cannot be explained with a simple formula.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 4 bytes of data (Big-endian).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each bit, from MSB to LSB, represents one of the next 32 PIDs and specifies whether that PID is supported.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 4 bytes of data, labeled A, B, C and D.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first byte (A) contains two pieces of information.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bit A7 (MSB of byte A) indicates whether or not the MIL (malfunction indicator light, aka. check engine light) is illuminated.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bits A6 through A0 represent the number of diagnostic trouble codes currently flagged in the ECU.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The second, third, and fourth bytes (B, C and D) give information about the availability and completeness of certain on-board tests ("OBD readiness checks").
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The third and fourth bytes are to be interpreted differently depending upon whether the engine is spark ignition (e.g.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Otto or Wankel engines) or compression ignition (e.g.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] In the second byte (B), bit 3 indicates the engine type and thus how to interpret bytes C and D, with 0 being spark (Otto or Wankel) and 1 (set) being compression (Diesel).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bits B6 to B4 and B2 to B0 are used for information about tests that not engine-type specific, and thus termed *common* tests.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Note that for bits indicating test **availability** a bit set to 1 indicates available, whilst for bits indicating test **completeness** a bit set to 0 indicates complete.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bytes C and D are mapped as follows for spark ignition engine types (e.g.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] NMHC *may* stand for Non-Methane HydroCarbons, but J1979 does not enlighten us.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The translation would be the ammonia sensor in the SCR catalyst.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 4 bytes of data.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The data returned is of an identical form to that returned for PID 01, with one exception - the first byte is always zero.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for one of these two PIDs will return 9 bytes of data.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] PID 78 returns data relating to EGT sensors for bank 1, whilst PID 79 similarly returns data for bank 2.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first byte is a bit encoded field indicating which EGT sensors are supported for the respective bank.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Bytes B through I provide 16-bit integers indicating the temperatures of the sensors.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The temperature values are interpreted in degrees Celsius in the range -40 to 6513.5 (scale 0.1), using the usual $(A\times 256+B)/10-40$ formula (MSB is A, LSB is B).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Only values for which the corresponding sensor is supported are meaningful.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this service returns a list of the DTCs that have been set.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The list is encapsulated using the ISO 15765-2 protocol.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] If there are two or fewer DTCs (up to 4 bytes) then they are returned in an ISO-TP Single Frame (SF).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Three or more DTCs in the list are reported in multiple frames, with the exact count of frames dependent on the communication type and addressing details.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Each trouble code requires 2 bytes to describe.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Encoded in these bytes are a category and a number.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] It is typically shown decoded into a five-character form like "U0158", where the first character (here 'U') represents the category the DTC belongs to, and the remaining four characters are a hexadecimal representation of the number under that category.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first two bits (A7 and A6) of the first byte (A) represent the category.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The remaining 14 bits represent the number.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Of note is that since the second character is formed from only two bits, it can thus only be within the range 0-3.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] "U0158", can be looked up in a table of OBD-II DTCs to get an actual description of what it represents.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Of note, whilst some blocks of DTC code ranges have generic meanings that apply to all vehicles and manufacturers, the meanings of others can vary per manufacturer or even model.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] It is also worth noting that DTCs may sometimes be encountered in a four-character form, e.g.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] "C158", which is simply the plain hexadecimal representation of the two bytes, with proper decoding with respect to the category not having been performed.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] It provides information about track in-use performance for catalyst banks, oxygen sensor banks, evaporative leak detection systems, EGR systems and secondary air system.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The numerator for each component or system tracks the number of times that all conditions necessary for a specific monitor to detect a malfunction have been encountered.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The denominator for each component or system tracks the number of times that the vehicle has been operated in the specified conditions.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The count of data items should be reported at the beginning (the first byte).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] All data items of the In-use Performance Tracking record consist of two bytes and are reported in this order (each message contains two items, hence the message length is 4).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] It provides information about track in-use performance for NMHC catalyst, NOx catalyst monitor, NOx adsorber monitor, PM filter monitor, exhaust gas sensor monitor, EGR/ VVT monitor, boost pressure monitor and fuel system monitor.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] Some PIDs are to be interpreted specially, and aren't necessarily exactly bitwise encoded, or in any scale.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The values for these PIDs are enumerated.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns 2 bytes of data.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The first byte describes fuel system #1.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The second byte describes fuel system #2 (if it exists) and is encoded identically to the first byte.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns a single byte of data which describes the secondary air status.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] A request for this PID returns a single byte of data which describes which OBD standards this ECU was designed to comply with.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] This PID returns a value from an enumerated list giving the fuel type of the vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] There are currently no definitions for flexible-fuel vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The majority of all OBD-II PIDs in use are non-standard.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] For most modern vehicles, there are many more functions supported on the OBD-II interface than are covered by the standard PIDs, and there is relatively minor overlap between vehicle manufacturers for these non-standard PIDs.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] There is very limited information available in the public domain for non-standard PIDs.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] The primary source of information on non-standard PIDs across different manufacturers is maintained by the US-based Equipment and Tool Institute and only available to members.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p01] However, even ETI membership will not provide full documentation for non-standard PIDs.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] As defined in ISO 15765-4, emissions protocols (including OBD-II, EOBD, UDS, etc.) use the ISO-TP transport layer (ISO 15765-2).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] All CAN frames sent using ISO-TP use a data length of 8 bytes (and DLC of 8).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] It is recommended to pad the unused data bytes with 0xCC.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] The PID query and response occurs on the vehicle's CAN bus.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Standard OBD requests and responses use functional addresses.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] The diagnostic reader initiates a query using CAN ID 7DFh, which acts as a broadcast address, and accepts responses from any ID in the range 7E8h to 7EFh.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] ECUs that can respond to OBD queries listen both to the functional broadcast ID of 7DFh and one assigned ID in the range 7E0h to 7E7h.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Their response has an ID of their assigned ID plus 8 e.g.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] This approach allows up to eight ECUs, each independently responding to OBD queries.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] The diagnostic reader can use the ID in the ECU response frame to continue communication with a specific ECU.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] In particular, multi-frame communication requires a response to the specific ECU ID rather than to ID 7DFh.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] CAN bus may also be used for communication beyond the standard OBD messages.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Physical addressing uses particular CAN IDs for specific modules (e.g., 720h for the instrument cluster in Fords) with proprietary frame payloads.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] The functional PID query is sent to the vehicle on the CAN bus at ID 7DFh, using 8 data bytes.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] The vehicle responds to the PID query on the CAN bus with message IDs that depend on which module responded.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Typically the engine or main ECU responds at ID 7E8h.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Other modules, like the hybrid controller or battery controller in a Prius, respond at 07E9h, 07EAh, 07EBh, etc.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] These are 8h higher than the physical address the module responds to.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Even though the number of bytes in the returned value is variable, the message uses 8 data bytes regardless (CAN bus protocol form Frameformat with 8 data bytes).
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] Same as query, except that 40h is added to the service value.
[src:obd-ii/obd-ii-pids-p02] 7Fh this a general response usually indicating the module doesn't recognize the request.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD systems give the vehicle owner or repair technician access to the status of the various vehicle sub-systems.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The amount of diagnostic information available via OBD has varied widely since its introduction in the early 1980s versions of onboard vehicle computers.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Early versions of OBD would simply illuminate a tell-tale light if a problem was detected, but would not provide any information as to the nature of the problem.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Modern OBD implementations use a standardized digital communications port to provide real-time data and diagnostic trouble codes which allow malfunctions within the vehicle to be rapidly identified.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] GM's ALDL (Assembly Line Diagnostic Link) is sometimes referred to as a predecessor to, or a manufacturer's proprietary version of, an OBD-I diagnostic starting in 1981.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] This interface was made in different varieties and changed with power train control modules (aka PCM, ECM, ECU).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Different versions had slight differences in pin-outs and baud rates.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Earlier versions used a 160 baud rate, while later versions went up to 8192 baud and used bi-directional communications to the PCM.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The regulatory intent of OBD-I was to encourage auto manufacturers to design reliable emission control systems that remain effective for the vehicle's "useful life".
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The hope was that by forcing annual emissions testing for California starting in 1988, and denying registration to vehicles that did not pass, drivers would tend to purchase vehicles that would more reliably pass the test.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-I was largely unsuccessful, as the means of reporting emissions-specific diagnostic information was not standardized.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Technical difficulties with obtaining standardized and reliable emissions information from all vehicles led to an inability to implement the annual testing program effectively.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTCs) of OBD-I vehicles can usually be found without an expensive scan tool.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Each manufacturer used their own Diagnostic Link Connector (DLC), DLC location, DTC definitions, and procedure to read the DTCs from the vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] DTCs from OBD-I cars are often read through the blinking patterns of the 'Check Engine Light' (CEL) or 'Service Engine Soon' (SES) light.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] By connecting certain pins of the diagnostic connector, the 'Check Engine' light will blink out a two-digit number that corresponds to a specific error condition.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The DTCs of some OBD-I cars are interpreted in different ways, however.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Cadillac fuel-injected vehicles are equipped with actual *onboard* diagnostics, providing trouble codes, actuator tests and sensor data through the new digital Electronic Climate Control display.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Holding down 'Off' and 'Warmer' for several seconds activates the diagnostic mode without the need for an external scan tool.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Some Honda engine computers are equipped with LEDs that light up in a specific pattern to indicate the DTC.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] General Motors, some 1989–1995 Ford vehicles (DCL), and some 1989–1995 Toyota/Lexus vehicles have a live sensor data stream available; however, many other OBD-I equipped vehicles do not.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-I vehicles have fewer DTCs available than OBD-II equipped vehicles.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD 1.5 refers to a partial implementation of OBD-II which General Motors used on some vehicles in 1994, 1995 & 1996 (GM did not use the term OBD 1.5 in the documentation for these vehicles — they simply had an OBD and an OBD-II section in the service manual).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For example, the 1994–1995 model year Corvettes have one post-catalyst oxygen sensor (although they have two catalytic converters), and have a subset of the OBD-II codes implemented.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For ALDL connections, pin 9 is the data stream, pins 4 and 5 are ground, and pin 16 is the battery voltage.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD 1.5 compatible scan tool is required to read codes generated by OBD 1.5.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Additional vehicle-specific diagnostic and control circuits are also available on this connector.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For instance, on the Corvette there are interfaces for the Class 2 serial data stream from the PCM, the CCM diagnostic terminal, the radio data stream, the airbag system, the selective ride control system, the low tire pressure warning system, and the passive keyless entry system.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD 1.5 has also been used in the Ford Scorpio since 95.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II is an improvement over OBD-I in both capability and standardization.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD-II standard specifies the type of diagnostic connector and its pinout, the electrical signalling protocols available, and the messaging format.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] It also provides a candidate list of vehicle parameters to monitor along with how to encode the data for each.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] There is a pin in the connector that provides power for the scan tool from the vehicle battery, which eliminates the need to connect a scan tool to a power source separately.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] However, some technicians might still connect the scan tool to an auxiliary power source to protect data in the unusual event that a vehicle experiences a loss of electrical power due to a malfunction.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Finally, the OBD-II standard provides an extensible list of DTCs.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] As a result of this standardization, a single device can query the on-board computer(s) in any vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] This OBD-II came in two models OBD-IIA and OBD-IIB.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II standardization was prompted by emissions requirements, and though only emission-related codes and data are required to be transmitted through it, most manufacturers have made the OBD-II Data Link Connector the only one in the vehicle through which all systems are diagnosed and programmed.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II Diagnostic Trouble Codes are 4-digit, preceded by a letter: P for powertrain (engine and transmission), B for body, C for chassis, and U for network.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD-II specification provides for a standardized hardware interface — the female 16-pin (2x8) J1962 connector, where type A is used for 12-volt vehicles and type B for 24-volt vehicles.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Unlike the OBD-I connector, which was sometimes found under the bonnet of the vehicle, the OBD-II connector is required to be within 2 feet (0.61 m) of the steering wheel (unless an exemption is applied for by the manufacturer, in which case it is still somewhere within reach of the driver).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The assignment of unspecified pins is left to the vehicle manufacturer's discretion.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For newly introduced models, the regulation dates applied a year earlier – January 1, 2000 for petrol and January 1, 2003, for diesel.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For passenger cars with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of greater than 2500 kg and for light commercial vehicles, the regulation dates applied from January 1, 2002, for petrol models, and January 1, 2007, for diesel models.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The technical implementation of EOBD is essentially the same as OBD-II, with the same SAE J1962 diagnostic link connector and signal protocols being used.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] With Euro V and Euro VI emission standards, EOBD emission thresholds are lower than previous Euro III and IV.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Each of the EOBD fault codes consists of five characters: a letter, followed by four numbers.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The letter refers to the system being interrogated e.g.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Pxxxx would refer to the powertrain system.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The next character would be a 0 if complies to the EOBD standard.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The next character would refer to the sub system.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The following two characters would refer to the individual fault within each subsystem.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The term "EOBD2" is marketing speak used by some vehicle manufacturers to refer to manufacturer-specific features that are not actually part of the OBD or EOBD standard.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] JOBD is a version of OBD-II for vehicles sold in Japan.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The ADR 79/01 Vehicle Standard (**A**ustralian **D**esign **R**ule **79/01** – Emission Control for Light Vehicles, 2005) is the Australian equivalent of OBD-II.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] It applies to all vehicles of category M1 and N1 with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of 3,500 kg (7,700 lb) or less, registered from new within Australia and produced since January 1, 2006 for petrol-engined cars and since January 1, 2007 for diesel-engined cars.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For newly introduced models, the regulation dates applied a year earlier – January 1, 2005 for petrol and January 1, 2006, for diesel.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The ADR 79/01 standard was supplemented by the ADR 79/02 standard which imposed tighter emissions restrictions, applicable to all vehicles of class M1 and N1 with a Gross Vehicle Weight rating of 3500 kg or less, from July 1, 2008, for new models, July 1, 2010, for all models.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The technical implementation of this standard is essentially the same as OBD-II, with the same SAE J1962 diagnostic link connector and signal protocols being used.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] In North America, EMD and EMD+ are on-board diagnostic systems that were used on vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of 14,000 lb (6,400 kg) or more between the 2007 and 2012 model years if those vehicles did not already implement OBD-II.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] EMD was used on California emissions vehicles between model years 2007 and 2009 that did not already have OBD-II.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] EMD was required to monitor fuel delivery, exhaust gas recirculation, the diesel particulate filter (on diesel engines), and emissions-related powertrain control module inputs and outputs for circuit continuity, data rationality, and output functionality.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] EMD+ was used on model year 2010-2012 California and Federal petrol-engined vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of over 14,000 lb (6,400 kg), it added the ability to monitor nitrogen oxide catalyst performance.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] EMD and EMD+ are similar to OBD-I in logic but use the same SAE J1962 data connector and CAN bus as OBD-II systems.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Five signaling protocols are permitted with the OBD-II interface.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Most vehicles implement only one of the protocols.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] All OBD-II pinouts use the same connector, but different pins are used with the exception of pin 4 (battery ground) and pin 16 (battery positive).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II provides access to data from the engine control unit (ECU) and offers a valuable source of information when troubleshooting problems inside a vehicle.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The SAE J1979 standard defines a method for requesting various diagnostic data and a list of standard parameters that might be available from the ECU.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The various available parameters are addressed by "parameter identification numbers" or **PID**s which are defined in J1979.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For a list of basic PIDs, their definitions, and the formula to convert raw OBD-II output to meaningful diagnostic units, see OBD-II PIDs.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Manufacturers are not required to implement all PIDs listed in J1979 and they are allowed to include proprietary PIDs that are not listed.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The PID request and data retrieval system gives access to real time performance data as well as flagged DTCs.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] For a list of generic OBD-II DTCs suggested by the SAE, see #OBD-II diagnostic trouble codes.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Individual manufacturers often enhance the OBD-II code set with additional proprietary DTCs.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Here is a basic introduction to the OBD communication protocol according to ISO 15031.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] In SAE J1979 these "modes" were renamed to "services", starting in 2003.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Various tools are available that plug into the OBD connector to access OBD functions.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] These range from simple generic consumer-level tools to sophisticated OEM dealership tools and vehicle telematic devices.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] A range of hand-held scan tools is available.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Mobile device applications allow mobile devices such as cell phones and tablets to display and manipulate OBD-II data accessed via USB adaptor cables or Bluetooth adapters plugged into the car's OBD II connector.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Newer devices on the market are equipped with GPS sensors and the ability to transmit vehicle location and diagnostics data over a cellular network.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Modern OBD-II devices can be used for locating vehicles and monitoring driving behavior in addition to reading Diagnostic Trouble Codes (DTC).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] More advanced devices allow users to reset engine DTCs, effectively turning off engine lights in the dashboard; however, resetting the codes does not address the underlying issues and can lead to engine damage if a serious issue is left unattended.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] An OBD-II software package, when installed on a computer (Windows, Mac, or Linux), can help diagnose the onboard system, read and erase DTCs, turn off the MIL, show real-time data, and measure vehicle fuel economy.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Using OBD-II software requires an OBD-II adapter (commonly using Bluetooth, Wi-Fi or USB) plugged into the OBD-II port to enable the vehicle to connect with the computer where the software is installed.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] A PC-based OBD analysis tool converts the OBD-II signals to a serial data format (USB or serial port) readable by PCs or Macs.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The software then decodes the received data for visual display.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Many interfaces are based on the ELM327 or STN OBD interpreter ICs, both of which read all five generic OBD-II protocols.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Some adapters now use the J2534 API, allowing them to access OBD-II protocols for both cars and trucks.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The extent that a PC tool may access manufacturer- or vehicle-specific ECU diagnostics varies between software products as it does between hand-held scanners.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Data loggers are designed to capture vehicle data while the vehicle is in normal operation for later analysis.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Analysis of vehicle black box data may be performed periodically, automatically transmitted wirelessly to a third party, or retrieved for forensic analysis after an event such as an accident, traffic infringement, or mechanical fault.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] In the United States, many states now use OBD-II testing instead of tailpipe testing in OBD-II-compliant vehicles (1996 and newer).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Since OBD-II stores trouble codes for emissions equipment, the testing computer can query the vehicle's onboard computer and verify there are no emission-related trouble codes and that the vehicle is in compliance with emission standards for the model year it was manufactured.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] In the Netherlands, 2006 and later vehicles get a yearly EOBD emission check.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Auto enthusiasts have traditionally installed additional gauges such as for manifold vacuum or battery current.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The OBD standard interface has enabled a new generation of enthusiast instrumentation accessing the full range of vehicle data used for diagnostics, as well as derived data such as instantaneous fuel economy.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Instrumentation may take the form of dedicated trip computers, carputers, or interfaces to PDAs, smartphones, or a Garmin navigation unit.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] As a carputer is essentially a PC, the same software could be loaded as for PC-based scan tools and vice versa; the distinction lies in the software's intended use.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] These enthusiast systems may also include some functionality similar to the other scan tools.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD II information is a data source for fleet telematics systems.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Devices that perform fleet management functions such as fleet tracking, monitoring fuel efficiency, and preventing unsafe driving often connect to the OBD-II port.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The port is also used for remote diagnostics and by pay-as-you-drive insurance.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Hundreds of different hardware manufacturers produce OBD-II telematics devices.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] These devices vary in their capabilities.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Some simpler GPS tracking devices use the OBD-II port only as a convenient source of power.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] More advanced devices, such as a telematic control unit, are able to access the vehicle's internal network to capture and decode a wide range of operational data.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Commonly supported OBD II data such as vehicle speed, RPM, and fuel level allow these devices to monitor vehicle idling times, speeding, and over-revving.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Monitoring OBD II DTCs can alert a company to a vehicle's engine problems by providing the relevant diagnostic code.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Other sensor data from the port can be used to detect unsafe driving in real time.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] This detection is done by adding a complex events processor (CEP) to the backend and on the client's interface.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD II is also monitored to block mobile phones when driving and to record trip data for insurance purposes.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] OBD-II diagnostic trouble codes (DTCs) are five characters long, with the first letter indicating a category, and the remaining four being a hexadecimal number.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The first character, representing category can only be one of the following four letters, given here with their associated meanings.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] (This restriction in number is due to how only two bits of memory are used to indicate the category when DTCs are stored and transmitted).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The second character is a number in the range of 0–3.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] (This restriction is again due to memory storage limitations).
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The third character may denote a particular vehicle system that the fault relates to.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Finally the fourth and fifth characters define the exact problem detected.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] In 2012, researchers at the University of Washington and University of California examined the security around OBD and found that they were able to gain control over many vehicle components via the interface.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Furthermore, they were able to upload new firmware into the engine control units.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] Their conclusion is that vehicle embedded systems are not designed with security in mind.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] There have been reports of thieves using specialist OBD reprogramming devices to enable them to steal cars without the use of a key.
[src:obd-ii/on-board-diagnostics] The primary causes of this vulnerability lie in the tendency for vehicle manufacturers to extend the bus for purposes other than those for which it was designed, and the lack of authentication and authorization in the OBD specifications, which instead rely largely on security through obscurity.
